To manage the rate at which you're making subrequests within a Cloudflare Worker and avoid hitting the "too many subrequests" error, you can implement a batching process. This process involves grouping your URLs into chunks and processing each group sequentially (or in limited parallelism) rather than attempting to process all URLs at once. Below is a way to refactor your code to fetch only 3 URLs at a time:

### Implementing Batching for Fetch Requests

```javascript
async function batchFetch(urls, batchSize) {
    let results = [];

    // Splitting the URLs into batches
    for (let i = 0; i < urls.length; i += batchSize) {
        const batch = urls.slice(i, i + batchSize);

        // Process each batch sequentially
        const responses = await Promise.all(
            batch.map(url => fetch(url, { method: 'HEAD', cf: { cacheTtl: -1 } }))
        );

        const batchResults = await Promise.all(responses.map(async (response, index) => {
            const size = parseInt(response.headers.get('Content-Length'), 10);
            return { url: batch[index], size };
        }));

        results = results.concat(batchResults);
    }

    return results;
}
```

